prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: 345GHz continuum observations
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: Dust continuum observations of 34 DSFGs related to the overdensity at z=2.2.

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: Main aim is to use the complete bandwidth of 7.5 GHz of the receivers in band 7.

In addition to detect the sources, we would like to study their morphology and size. Therefore, we request a resolution of 0.2arcsec which should be good enough to resolve the sources, see Simpson et al. (2015).

The fluxes of our sources at 870micron lie between 1.5 to 12 mJy. Therefore, for faint sources we would get at least a 5sigma detection for the faintest sources. Furthermore, with the proposed RMS we will also be able to get solid detections of at least 3sigma in cases where the targeted SMG consists of multiple components (e.g. Wang et al. 2011, Smolcic et al. 2012, Karim et al. 2013). The position uncertainty of our sources will be well covered by the primary beam of 18arcsec. The chosen frequency corresponds to the wavelengths of our LABOCA observations and thus will be an independent check of the fluxes derived from the bolometer map. E.g. missing fluxes in the ALMA band could indicate either multiple, fainter counterparts and/or extended submm emission.
We chose the standard correlator set-up for continuum observations. In order to match the frequency of our APEX LABOCA observations at 870micron we set the sky frequency to 345GHz.

prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: CO(4-3) and CI observations
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: CO(4-3) and CI observations in band 4 of 25 DSFGs related to the overdensity at z=2.2

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText: The CO(4-3) transition will be centered in baseband 2 and C(1-0) in baseband 3. The remaining two baseband 1/4 are placed on either sides in order to enlarge the frequency coverage for a better continuum measurement. We require a standard spectral line setup with four 1.9 GHz basebands, yielding in 3900 km/s velocity coverage per baseband. The expected line width is FWHM=500km/s, thus the setup covers both the line and a large number of line-free channels for continuum subtraction. For basebands 2/3 we choose a channel width of 1MHz (2km/s), and if necessary, we will bin the data in velocity in order to increase the sensitivity. In order to reduce the data rate we applied a spectral averaging reaching of 2 on baseband 2/3 being good enough for our purpose. For basebands 1/4 containing the continuum we choose a channel width of 31MHz.
This will be a detection experiment. At a resolution of 2 arcsec we expect our sources to be still point sources which is enough for this detection experiment.

We request spectroscopic observations of the CO(4-3), redshifted to band 4. We note that the CI(1-0) line is also present in this band but the large variation in the L_CO(4-3)/L_C(1-0) ratio (Alaghband-Zadeh et al. 2013, MNRAS, 435, 1493) means that we base these calculation on the CO(4-3) line. Using our LABOCA and Herschel observations we estimate IR-Luminosities between 2.5-17.9x10^12 L_sun. This translates into L'_CO(1-0) luminosities of at least 2-3x10^10 K km s^-1 pc^2 (Ivison et al. 2011, MNRAS, 412, 1913). Taking into account median brightness temperature ratio of r_43=0.41 (Bothwell et al. 2013, MNRAS, 429, 3047), we aim to achieve an integrated line intensity of at least I_CO(4-3)=0.6 Jy km/s for the CO(4-3) transition. The typical FWHM value of submm galaxies is 500 km/s (Bothwell et al. 2013). Adopting this value, we estimate flux density >=1.2mJy for CO(4-3). Therefore, an rms sensitivity of 0.4 mJy will ensure we detect the line at the >=3 sigma level.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: Protoclusters, ancestors of local galaxy clusters, provide a unique opportunity to trace the emergence of large-scale structure, and to study galaxy evolution in dense environments. Our submm imaging with APEX LABOCA and Herschel PACS+SPIRE has uncovered an overdensity of dusty star forming galaxies related to the protocluster field of the radio galaxy MRC1138-262 at z=2.16. We propose ALMA 870micron dust continuum imaging and CO(4-3)+CI molecular line observations of all the candidate protocluster starburst galaxies. Major aims of this work will be the determination of the membership, characterization of the mass of the molecular gas reservoirs, the gas depletion time scale, the star formation efficiency of these massive dusty cluster members and the size of the starburst. This will be the first high-z cluster field with a statistically significant number of galaxies with CO detetions. We will compare the properties of our SMGs located in a high density region with dusty starbursts selected from blank fields, probing environmental-dependent evolution. Studying the ISM of the individual members will enable us to characterize in more detail the overall properties of this structure.
